# **Technical Documentation: Perfect Cup of Coffee**

## 1\. Overview

"Perfect Cup of Coffee" is an AI-powered application that analyzes coffee packages and user preferences to recommend optimal brewing parameters. The system combines OCR technology for image analysis with recommendation algorithms to provide personalized coffee brewing guidance.

## 2\. Tech Stack

* Backend: Python with FastHTML framework  
* AI Components: MistralAI API for Vision-Model and LLM capabilities  
* Agent Orchestration: ControlFlow framework  
* Data Validation: Pydantic models  
* Frontend: HTML with Tailwind CSS  
* Image Processing: Base64 encoding/decoding  
* Data Storage: Local file system with optional Google Sheets integration

## 3\. Process Architecture

![agentic_flow](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/338b769f-9370-4547-a4a1-8ea03c76986f)
follows a modular architecture with four distinct layers:

* User Interface Layer: Handles user interaction through web forms and image uploads  
* Data Storage Layer: Manages temporary image storage and coffee profile data  
* Processing Layer: Contains the core business logic modules  
* AI Models Layer: Integrates with Mistral's AI services for OCR and natural language tasks

The data flows from user inputs through processing pipelines to generate personalized brewing recommendations.

## 4\. Detailed Agentic Architecture

![architecture](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/5efae409-57a8-4360-9e62-14125773d5dc)
system leverages an agentic workflow architecture:

1. Request Processing: Routes user inputs to appropriate handlers  
2. Image Analysis: For uploaded coffee packages, performs OCR and extracts structured data  
3. Preference Processing: Processes user taste preferences  
4. Agent Orchestration: Coordinates multiple AI agents through ControlFlow  
5. Result Generation: Combines extracted data and preferences to generate recommendations

## 5\. Core Components

## **OCR Module (modules/ocr.py)**

* Extracts text from coffee package images using Mistral OCR API  
* Processes the extracted text to identify key coffee attributes  
* Structures data using Pydantic models

## **Vision Module (modules/vision.py)**

* Handles image preprocessing and encoding  
* Interfaces with Mistral's vision capabilities  
* Extracts coffee information directly from images

## **Agent Configuration (modules/agent\_config.py)**

* Sets up LLM agents with specific roles  
* Configures agent parameters (temperature, token limits)  
* Creates dedicated agents for OCR processing and recommendation generation

## **Recommendation Engine (modules/recommender.py)**

* Maps user preferences to coffee characteristics  
* Generates brewing parameters based on coffee attributes  
* Provides structured recommendations with explanations

## 6\. Data Flow Process

1. Input Collection:  
   * User submits taste preferences via form inputs (intensity, flavor profile, acidity)  
   * Optional: User uploads coffee package image  
2. Image Processing (if image provided):  
   * Image is saved to temporary storage  
   * Base64 encoding is applied for API transmission  
   * Mistral OCR extracts text from the image  
   * Structured coffee information is extracted from OCR text  
3. Recommendation Generation:  
   * User preferences are mapped to coffee profiles  
   * Coffee attributes are mapped to brewing parameters  
   * ControlFlow agents generate tailored recommendations  
   * Results are formatted as structured JSON with brewing parameters  
4. Response Delivery:  
   * Results are displayed to the user in the web interface  
   * Optional: Data is saved to Google Sheets for future analysis

## 7\. Key Features and Implementation Details

## **Coffee Attribute Extraction**

The system extracts four key attributes from coffee packages:

* Origin/Country: Categorized into regional groups (Central/South America, Asia-Pacific, Africa)  
* Roast Level: Identified as light, medium-light, medium, medium-dark, or dark  
* Variety: Classified as Arabica, Robusta, or blends  
* Process: Categorized as natural, washed, or honey processed

## **Brewing Parameter Recommendation**

The system generates specific brewing parameters:

* Water: for ex., 93¬∞C  
* Ratio: for ex.,1:16 (but could be between 1:15 to 1:18 falling in line with espresso machine standard ratios)
* Time: for ex., 2:30 mins (pour-over)  
* Grind: for ex., Medium-coarse

## **Error Handling**

* Fallback mechanisms for OCR failures  
* Default recommendations when specific data is unavailable  
* JSON parsing with error recovery strategies  
* Exception handling throughout the pipeline

## 8\. Future Improvements

As outlined in the project README:
We've implemented a feedback loop that will allow the system to continuously improve as users report their actual results, creating a self-optimizing recommendation engine.
## ** Actionable Insights from nunc Dataset
After investigating the dataset in terms of devide ID 10000000812efd14, recipe ID 31, here are actinable insights:
* (water temperature) There is a slight decrease in brewer temperature when water comes into the coffee ground, and it increases later on. The temperature shall ideally remain stable and constant throughout the brewing process
* (water volume) There is an obvious change of water flow during brewing. In order to asure consistency, such change shall be avoid.
* (pressure) In one device with one coffee recipe, circuit pressure varies largely in brewing. For making a good coffee a constant and stable pressure is desired.

### üí∞ Value Sweet Spot
